text=:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages%0a:Essential: {Category.PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages$:essential}%0a:Title: Epenthesis in spoken English by Mandarin speakers%0a:Author: yuluz%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 27.03.2021 - 07:45%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210418-225445-676610#%0a* [-18.04.2021 - 15:54-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210418-225445-676610#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn Mandarin, syllables do not start with complex onset or ending in non-nasal codas, so native mandarin speakers tend to repair the illicit onset and coda components in English with epenthesis.  %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn Mandarin Chinese (Sino-Tibetan),a syllable does not start with a complex onset, neither does it end in any coda except for nasals [n] and [ŋ]. The typical syllable structure in Mandarin would be a simple onset with a nucleus of one or two vowels (CV,CVV) or a simple onset followed by a vowel and a nasal coda (CVC). %0a%0aThis structure causes Mandarin speakers to struggle a bit with pronouncing English syllables that start with complex onsets or end with non-nasal codas. The way they repair it is by inserting vowels in between consonants in the complex onset and after the coda. %0a%0aExamples of how Mandarin speakers use epenthesis to repair English words with complex onsets include: "fry" as [fuɹaɪ], “play” as [puleɪ], and “glad” as [gəlæd]. Examples of epenthesis after English coda include: "job" as [ʤɑbu], "check" as [ʧɛkə], “dog” as [dɔgə]. An example of epenthesis in both onset and coda in a single word is “great”, which tend to be pronounced as [guɹeɪtə] by Mandarin speakers. %0a%0aFrom these examples, we can see that the consonant cluster of an obstruent followed by a sonorant seem unnatural to Mandarin speakers and require insertion of a vowel to break them up. Furthermore, we see that [ə] is added after velar and alveolar plosives, while [u] is added after bilabial plosives /p/ and /b/.%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
